For the force by which a rigid body is bent tends to produce all these results. For I think it is the case always that if a force seeks to effect something and there are various ways in which it may attain the result, while yet there is in all of them great resistance and difficulty, the force Ι say endeavours to perform the thing in these several ways Hence since a rigid body can be bent, as was pre- viously shown, either by the approximation of the convex to the concave side, or by the elongation of the one or the shortening of the other, or lastly by the in- clination to each other of the end planes; and since ' there is at the same time great resistance to the bending ol the rigid body by any of the methods (for the matter of a rigid body is so dense and compact, that its sides cannot without difficulty be drawn towards each other; its sides also are so firm and solid that they cannot be lengthened or shortened without great pressure), hence I say the force by which one tries to bend a rigid body has enough to do in effecting its purpose in those several ways. Still, however, while the rigid body is bending at the same time in all of these ways, its matter suffers a notable compression, especially at the middle, as is evident from what has Α been said.
